Moutafidis Christos

2024-02-10

Hello, this case study is about Video game sales and the Critic/User score, I Downloaded the Data base from a kaggle user named: DIMA806. This data set contains data from 2016, so the results may vary from todays standars.

Videogame Sales and Scores

Now that we have the Column names, we can start by finding what we think that is important for the audience to see, for my analysis I wanted to find the: 1. Best selling Platform of all time.(the platform that has sold the most games) 2. Best selling game per Platform. 3. Best selling Genres. 4. Best selling games in those Genres. 5. Best User Scored Game. 6. Best Critic’s Scored Game. 7. Most Sold Video game of all time.

Let us begin then.

I start by Viewing the best Genres (I want to keep the Most sold Video game for last).

ggplot(data = Video_Games) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(y= Genre))

From this plot we can Visualize the top Genres. 1. Action. 2. Sports. 3. Misc. 4. Role_Playing(AKA RPG). 5. Shooters

Now lets find the Best sellers per Gaming Genre.

Now if you look closely, you will see that some of the games have less than 10 Users who rated the games, that’s not good! so how do we change it?

Top_Ranked_Games_By_User <- Video_Games
Top_Ranked_Games_By_User <- filter(Top_Ranked_Games_By_User, User_Count > 200)
Top_Ranked_Games_By_User <- arrange(Top_Ranked_Games_By_User, desc(User_Score))
Top_Ranked_Games_By_User <- head(Top_Ranked_Games_By_User,5)
head(Top_Ranked_Games_By_User,5)
